<section id="sparql" class="section">
  <div class="section-head">
    <div>
      <div class="eyebrow">SPARQL Analysis</div>
      <h2>Query overview before detailed analysis</h2>
    </div>
    <p>Five SPARQL queries were selected to demonstrate different ways of exploring, checking and organizing knowledge graph data.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="grid-4">
    <div class="card"><div class="query-number">1</div><h3>Basic Exploration</h3><p>Retrieve all available metadata about the monument.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><div class="query-number">2</div><h3>DISTINCT</h3><p>Verify heritage designation and retrieve unique values.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><div class="query-number">3</div><h3>OPTIONAL</h3><p>Identify missing information in the Wikidata entry.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><div class="query-number">4</div><h3>FILTER</h3><p>Exclude unnecessary data and focus on relevant metadata.</p></div>
  </div>

  <div class="grid-2" style="margin-top:18px">
    <div class="card"><div class="query-number">5</div><h3>ORDER BY + LIMIT</h3><p>Organize results alphabetically and limit output size.</p></div>
    <div class="card gold">
      <h3>SPARQL Logic</h3>
      <p><strong>Exploration → Verification → Missing Data → Filtering → Organization</strong></p>
      <p>Together, the queries show the current state of the Wikidata entry and support knowledge gap identification.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="section-head">
    <div>
      <div class="eyebrow">SPARQL Details</div>
      <h2>Query 1–5 with evidence</h2>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card query-card">
    <h3>Query 1 — Basic Exploration</h3>
    <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> To retrieve all available properties and values associated with the Mausoleum of Khoja Ahmed Yasawi.</p>
<pre>SELECT ?propertyLabel ?valueLabel
WHERE {
  wd:Q46069 ?p ?value .
  ?property wikibase:directClaim ?p .

  SERVICE wikibase:label {
    bd:serviceParam wikibase:language "en".
    ?property rdfs:label ?propertyLabel .
    ?value rdfs:label ?valueLabel .
  }
}
LIMIT 50</pre>
    <div class="proof"><strong>Proof:</strong> The query returned 32 metadata records, including country = Kazakhstan, location = Turkistan, architectural style = Timurid architecture, heritage designation = World Heritage Site, commissioned by = Timur, and inception = 1400.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="card query-card">
    <h3>Query 2 — DISTINCT</h3>
    <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> To identify the heritage status of the monument and retrieve unique heritage designations.</p>
<pre>SELECT DISTINCT ?heritageLabel
WHERE {
  wd:Q46069 wdt:P1435 ?heritage .

  SERVICE wikibase:label {
    bd:serviceParam wikibase:language "en".
    ?heritage rdfs:label ?heritageLabel .
  }
}</pre>
    <div class="proof"><strong>Proof:</strong> The query confirmed that the monument is recognized as a World Heritage Site. DISTINCT ensured that duplicate heritage values were avoided.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="card query-card">
    <h3>Query 3 — Detecting Missing Information with OPTIONAL</h3>
    <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> To check whether Wikidata contains information about the architect of the monument.</p>
<pre>SELECT ?itemLabel ?architectLabel
WHERE {
  VALUES ?item { wd:Q46069 }

  OPTIONAL { ?item wdt:P84 ?architect . }

  SERVICE wikibase:label {
    bd:serviceParam wikibase:language "en".
  }
}</pre>
    <div class="proof"><strong>Proof:</strong> The query returned the monument but no architect value. This shows that architect information is missing or not explicitly represented in Wikidata.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="card query-card">
    <h3>Query 4 — Refining Results with FILTER</h3>
    <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> To exclude image-related information and focus on descriptive metadata.</p>
<pre>SELECT ?propertyLabel ?valueLabel
WHERE {
  wd:Q46069 ?p ?value .
  ?property wikibase:directClaim ?p .

  FILTER(?property != wd:P18)

  SERVICE wikibase:label {
    bd:serviceParam wikibase:language "en".
    ?property rdfs:label ?propertyLabel .
    ?value rdfs:label ?valueLabel .
  }
}
LIMIT 20</pre>
    <div class="proof"><strong>Proof:</strong> The query returned metadata such as country, material, location, architectural style, UNESCO ID and heritage criteria while excluding the image property.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="card query-card">
    <h3>Query 5 — Organizing Metadata with ORDER BY and LIMIT</h3>
    <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> To sort the metadata alphabetically and limit the output to 15 rows.</p>
<pre>SELECT ?propertyLabel ?valueLabel
WHERE {
  wd:Q46069 ?p ?value .
  ?property wikibase:directClaim ?p .

  SERVICE wikibase:label {
    bd:serviceParam wikibase:language "en".
    ?property rdfs:label ?propertyLabel .
    ?value rdfs:label ?valueLabel .
  }
}
ORDER BY ?propertyLabel
LIMIT 15</pre>
    <div class="proof"><strong>Proof:</strong> Results included World Heritage Site ID = 1103, World Heritage criteria = (i), (iii), (iv), TDV Encyclopedia of Islam ID, Commons category, Library of Congress authority ID and Kazakhstan.travel tourist spot ID.</div>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="gaps" class="section">
  <div class="section-head">
    <div>
      <div class="eyebrow">Knowledge Gaps</div>
      <h2>Missing or underrepresented information</h2>
    </div>
    <p>SPARQL exploration showed that Wikidata contains factual metadata, but not all cultural and religious meanings are represented.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="grid-2">
    <div class="card"><h3>Gap 1 — Connection with Yasawiyya Sufi Order</h3><p>The connection between the mausoleum and the Yasawiyya Sufi tradition is not explicitly modeled in Wikidata.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><h3>Gap 2 — Role as a Pilgrimage Site</h3><p>The mausoleum is culturally understood as a pilgrimage destination, but this role is not clearly represented in Wikidata.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><h3>Gap 3 — Spiritual and Religious Significance</h3><p>The knowledge graph lacks deeper information about the spiritual and religious meaning of the site.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><h3>Gap 4 — Related Religious Heritage Sites</h3><p>Connections with related religious heritage sites in Kazakhstan are not explicitly represented.</p></div>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="llm" class="section">
  <div class="section-head">
    <div>
      <div class="eyebrow">LLM Evaluation</div>
      <h2>LLM Comparison: ChatGPT and Gemini</h2>
    </div>
    <p>We used three prompting techniques to compare the usefulness of ChatGPT and Gemini for RDF enrichment.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="grid-2">
    <div class="photo three"></div>
    <div class="card">
      <h3>Prompting Techniques</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Zero-shot:</strong> no example was provided.</li>
        <li><strong>Few-shot:</strong> an RDF example was provided before the task.</li>
        <li><strong>Chain-of-Thought:</strong> the model was asked to reason step by step.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>ChatGPT produced more focused outputs aligned with the research questions. Gemini generated richer and more exploratory semantic suggestions.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div style="margin-top:26px">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Prompting Technique</th><th>ChatGPT</th><th>Gemini</th><th>Human Assessment</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Zero-shot</td><td>Generated concise RDF triples focused on the identified gaps.</td><td>Generated richer semantic relations and explanations.</td><td>Both models were relevant. ChatGPT was clearer; Gemini was more descriptive.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Few-shot</td><td>Followed the example structure and produced consistent triples.</td><td>Introduced more complex semantic relations.</td><td>Few-shot improved both models.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Chain-of-Thought</td><td>Stayed close to the research questions and identified gaps.</td><td>Generated additional ideas but sometimes moved beyond the project scope.</td><td>ChatGPT was more focused; Gemini was more exploratory.</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>
</section>

